flowRoot.flowPara: GPS/GNSS data have high accuracy and temporal resolution but are spatially sparse. These data often need to be interpolated on regular grids (e.g., to be used as constraints during InSAR processing). Interpolation is done separately for each component of the velocity vector. Sandwell and Wessel (2016) proposed Green's functions based joint interpolation of the horizontal components, which are coupled through elasticity. We propose an extension of this method to include the vertical component, enabling the inclusion of vector data projected in arbitrary directions, such as InSAR line-of-sight velocities.

The Green's functions we adopted for interpolation are a solution to Cerruti's problem for an elastic half-space (Okumura, 1995). Given the x, y, z components of M forces, we can calculate the x, y, z components of N displacements at arbitrary locations. We introduce a new "coupling parameter" to control the degree of coupling between the vertical and horizontal components.
Fig 1: Elastic half-space with a force acting on it's surface and the corresponding displacement vector.

Assuming that our measured vectors are the displacements, we can formulate this as a matrix equation and solve for the forces that best fit our data in a least-squares sense. We use damping regularization to stabilize the solution and avoid over-fitting. Interpolation is done by forward modeling the displacements using our best-fit forces.

flowRoot.flowPara: We employed cross-validation techniques to automatically select optimal values for controlling parameters of the interpolation. Cross-validation works by splitting the dataset into two parts: one for fitting the interpolator (the training set) and one for evaluating the interpolator's performance (the testing set). In particular, we used k-fold cross-validation, in which the dataset is randomly shuffled and split k times for a more robust measure of performance.
